{
  "id": "gravitational-pe",
  "title": "Gravitational energy: why escape velocity is finite",
  "topic": "gravitation",
  "slug": "potential-energy",
  "scenario": "Lifting a mass away from a planet ($\\mu = GM = 4\\times10^{14}$ m³/s², surface radius $R = 6.4\\times10^{6}$ m): the gravitational pull weakens as $F = GMm/r^2$. How much energy does it take to climb — and why is the energy to escape *finite*? Drag the cursor outward and watch the potential energy approach a ceiling as the area under $1/r^2$ converges.",
  "regime": 2,
  "constants": {
    "mu": 400000000000000.0,
    "R": 6400000.0,
    "m": 1.0
  },
  "initial_conditions": {},
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "claim": "Spherically symmetric planet, so outside the surface the field is $GMm/r^2$ (point-mass equivalent).",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "Only gravity acts; the lift is quasi-static (no kinetic energy bookkeeping — this is the potential energy alone).",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "$\\mu = GM$ is used so the force is unit-clean; energies are shown per kilogram ($m = 1$ kg).",
      "kind": "model"
    }
  ],
  "algebra": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "What the algebra-based course hands you",
        "latex": "\\Delta U = mgh \\quad(\\text{near the surface, } g \\text{ constant})",
        "prose": "Close to the ground, gravity is treated as a constant $mg$, so the potential energy is $mgh$ — the area of a rectangle. But gravity weakens with distance ($F\\propto 1/r^2$), so this fails once $h$ is comparable to the planet's radius. There is no algebra formula for the energy to reach orbit or escape."
      }
    ],
    "result": {
      "pe_to_2R": {
        "label": "PE gained reaching $r=2R$",
        "unit": "J",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\tfrac{GMm}{2R}",
        "value": 31250000.0,
        "display": "31250000"
      },
      "escape_energy": {
        "label": "Escape energy $GMm/R$ (area to $\\infty$)",
        "unit": "J",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\tfrac{GMm}{R}",
        "value": 62500000.0,
        "display": "62500000"
      },
      "surface_force": {
        "label": "Surface weight $F(R)=GMm/R^2=mg$",
        "unit": "N",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\tfrac{GMm}{R^2}",
        "value": 9.765625,
        "display": "9.766"
      }
    }
  },
  "calculus": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "Potential energy is the area under the force–distance curve",
        "latex": "\\Delta U = \\int_R^r F\\,dr' = \\int_R^r \\frac{GMm}{r'^2}\\,dr'",
        "prose": "The work to lift a mass against gravity is the integral of the force over distance — the area under the $F$–$r$ curve. For a constant force this is a rectangle ($mgh$); for the inverse-square force it is the area under a falling curve."
      },
      {
        "label": "Evaluate the inverse-square integral",
        "latex": "\\Delta U = GMm\\left(\\frac{1}{R} - \\frac{1}{r}\\right)",
        "prose": "The area under $1/r^2$ from $R$ to $r$ is $GMm(1/R - 1/r)$. Its slope at any radius is $GMm/r^2 = F(r)$ — the force is the rate at which potential energy accumulates."
      },
      {
        "label": "The escape energy is finite — the area converges",
        "latex": "\\boxed{\\,\\lim_{r\\to\\infty}\\Delta U = \\frac{GMm}{R}\\,}",
        "prose": "Push the cursor outward and the PE rises toward a *finite* ceiling, even as $r\\to\\infty$: the area under $1/r^2$ converges. That ceiling is the escape energy — and SymPy proves the limit. A constant force would give an infinite area; the inverse square does not.",
        "emphasis": true
      }
    ]
  },
  "proof": {
    "kind": "integral",
    "heading": "Gravitational PE is the area under the force curve — and the area to infinity converges to a finite escape energy.",
    "checked_by": "sympy",
    "holds": true,
    "detail": "check $\\tfrac{d}{dr}\\Delta U = F$; check $\\Delta U = \\int_R^r F\\,dr'$; check $\\lim_{r\\to\\infty}\\Delta U = GMm/R$; collapse the near-surface case to $mgh$",
    "checks": [
      {
        "key": "ftc_slope",
        "claim": "The PE's slope is the force: $U'(r) = F(r)$ — the area's rate of growth is the curve's height.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "area_is_integral",
        "claim": "The accumulated PE is the area: $\\Delta U(r) = \\int_R^r F\\,dr'$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "escape_is_finite",
        "claim": "The area to infinity converges: the escape energy $\\to GMm/R$ is finite as $r\\to\\infty$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "flat_earth_echo",
        "claim": "Near the surface $F\\approx mg$ is constant, so $\\Delta U \\approx mgh$ — the area is a rectangle (the quadrature).",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      }
    ]
  },
